  ],
  "text": "Firefox's content process lifecycle in the dom/ipc/ directory is managed through several key classes:\n\n1. **ContentParent** (github.com/sg-evals/firefox--871325b8, dom/ipc/ContentParent.h/cpp): The parent-side manager for content processes. ContentParent is a final class that inherits from PContentParent and multiple interfaces (nsIDOMProcessParent, nsIObserver, etc.), serving as the primary mechanism for parent process communication with child content processes.\n\n2. **ContentProcessManager** (github.com/sg-evals/firefox--871325b8, dom/ipc/ContentProcessManager.h/cpp): A singleton registry that tracks all active content processes. ContentProcessManager maintains hash maps of ContentParent and BrowserParent objects, indexed by process IDs and tab IDs, allowing efficient lookup and management of processes and tabs.\n\n3. **BrowserParent** (github.com/sg-evals/firefox--871325b8, dom/ipc/BrowserParent.h/cpp): The parent-side representation of a remote tab. BrowserParent implements the PBrowserParent protocol and manages communication with the corresponding BrowserChild in the content process, handling window events, rendering, and other tab-specific operations.\n\n4. **PreallocatedProcessManager** and **PreallocatedProcessManagerImpl** (github.com/sg-evals/firefox--871325b8, dom/ipc/PreallocatedProcessManager.h/cpp): The preallocation pool manager that maintains a pool of preallocated content processes for faster process spawning. PreallocatedProcessManager provides static public methods, while PreallocatedProcessManagerImpl implements the actual functionality and inherits from nsIObserver to handle lifecycle events.\n\nThese four components work together to manage the complete content process lifecycle: process creation (via PreallocatedProcessManager), registry management (via ContentProcessManager), parent-side coordination (via ContentParent), and per-tab communication (via BrowserParent)."
}

